name.y: Great Barrier Reef - Marine National Park Zone
fishing_in:
The Marine National Park (Green) Zone is a 'no-take' area and extractive activities like fishing or collecting are not allowed without a permit.
The Marine National Park (Green) Zone makes up about 33 per cent of the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park.

name.x: Channel Islands National Marine Sanctuary Marine Reserve Network
other_docs: Channel Islands NMS Condition Report 2016 (Reviewed), California MPA Master Plan 2016 and Action Plan 2018 (NR), US Framework for National System of MPAs (NR)
network.x: California Coastal MPA Network - South Coast Region, US National Network of MPAs
obj_details: Conservation Action Plan (part of MP) explicitly lists monitoring/evaluating effects of climate change as a priority issue, making CINMS operations "green", and monitoring and planning for invasive species
va_details: CCVA was completed for deepwater corals (2014) but a comprehensive vulnerability assessment has not been reported. However, the Condition Report (2016) evaluates many specific climate change stressors and there have been other environmental impact analyses. These have directly translated into adaptation activities. Stressors: ocean acidification, reductions in disollved oxygen, HABs, warming, marine heat waves
des_cc: Emphasizing network design; adaptive management plans include updating design for climate change (Boundary Evaluation Action Plan)
sci_monitor: Extensive (keystone and foundation species, ex. kelp forest and shallow rock habitats, biomass of focal species - targeted and non-targeted/algae/inverts, water quality, climate change drivers,
social_monitor: Extensive (water quality, shipping, marine debris, oil activity)
cc_monitor_det: Tracking climate indicators (e.g. water temperature, acidity, disollved oxygen) and changes in ecological communities (e.g. deep sea corals); evaluate multiple stressors/drivers and their interactions for a variety of targets, examining how species richness and diversity of fauna are influenced by short- and long-term changes including range shifts and expansions/contractions
network.y: Channel Islands National Marine Sanctuary, California MPA Network
fishing_in: The entire MPA network consists of 11 marine reserves where all take and harvest is prohibited

other_docs: Southern Belize Reef Complex Conservation Action Plan
protection: Zoning - Conservation Zone I and II and Preservation Zone are all NT
network.x: Belize Barrier Reef Protected Area System, Southern Belize Reef Complex
sp_feat: System level targets with additional nested targets
unit_feat: System level targets with additional nested targets
obj_details: Each feature has an associated goal and indicators (e.g. for coral reefs - return system to a healthy state; measured by % cover, % macroalgae, reef fish density). For climate change, there is an explicit management goal and strategies - identify resilient coral species, recruitment sources, ensure herbivore protection, reduce cumulative anthropogenic local threats, monitor climate change effects, and characterize water currents critical for recruitment of coral/fish. "By 2015 at least 50% of coral reefs and mangroves resilient to climate change located within the SBRC will be effectively protected."
va_details: General assessment of the status of features with respect to various other threats, and a specific "site reilience assessment" with respect to climate change; Sea level rise, SST rise, increased storm frequency, ocean acidification, decreased precipitation, air temperature changes
sci_monitor: In development; some monitoring already conducted (e.g. coral bleaching)
social_monitor: In development; some monitoring already conducted (e.g. coral bleaching)
cc_monitor_det: Emphasizing establishing adequate baseline information for monitoring targets for climate change adaptation and limits of acceptable change, continuing to add monitoring for climate change, integrating climate change into research priorities, identifying areas with/without resilience to climate change. Already monitor some climate-related variables and impacts (e.g. coral bleaching)
am_det: Zoning revision, updates to boundaries considered; 5 year MP review
act_type: ED, IP, CO, TO, LE, HR, PO, IS

name.x: British Virgin Islands Marine Reserve Network
sp_feat: Commercial species, valuable wildlife, endangered and critical species (turtles, seabirds)
unit_feat: Habitats important for productivity, representativeness, diversity, physiographic/geologic/aesthetically unique areas
va_details: Objective to conduct assessments of vulnerability to climate change and sea level rise
des_res: Yes - based on turtle nesting beaches, protected and important seagrass areas, mangrove stands, coral reefs (areas with Montastrea and Acropora species) and existing Fisheries and Marine PAs; target cover 30% of nearshore habitats and ecosystems, moderate size (10-100km2) and variable spacing, placement balancing conservation/tourism impacts/fisheries management
am_det: System-wide evaluation every 5 years; includes updates in site planning, consolidation of units (currently planned - addressing issues of minimum size, connectivity), consultations of management plans

name.x: Ross Sea Region Marine Protected Area
sp_feat: Trophically dominant pelagic prey species (Antarctic krill, crystal krill, Antarctic silverfish), areas important in life cycle of Antarctic toothfish, top predators or those which compete with fisheries (Adelie penguins, emperor penguins, Weddell seals, Type C killer whales)
unit_feat: Habitats important to native organisms; conserve structure and function at all biological levels, biodiversity (representative benthic and pelagic environments), large-scale ecosystem processes (shelf front interaction with seasonal ice, Polar frton, Balleny Islands and proximity, polynya marginal ice zone, multi-year ice), core foraging areas for land-based predators, rare/vulnerable benthic habitats (seamounts, slopes, McMurdo Sound, underwater features)

va_details: Qualitative risk assessment was conducted to prioritize issues for management based on stressors in the region - climate change and variability was one category. Stressors: SST anomalies, acidification, thermal fronts/surges, wind patterns, precipitation patterns, seasonal temperature changes, and heat waves
